http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A roughly cylindrical body, which may reduce in diameter at one end like a funnel
Body geometry is irregular and can not be characterized using terminology.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: Glossary of Geology. 4th Edition, AGI + DC, adapted from

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A body bounded by converging surfaces (at least one of which is curved), thick in the middle and thinning out toward the edges, resembling a convex lens.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: Glossary of Geology. 5th Edition, AGI, definition (b)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Having the shape of a nodule or occurring in the form of nodules; e.g. "nodular ore" such as a colloform mineral aggregate with a bulbed surface.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: Dictionary of Mining 2nd ed, AGI 1997, adapted from

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A roughly cylindrical body having a diameter that decreases to zero at both ends like a cigar or a potato.
Having a curved form like a fold hinge

http://purl.org/dc/terms/source.value: Dictionary of Mining 2nd ed, AGI 1997, adapted from

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A body having two dimensions that are much larger or longer than the third, e.g. a dyke-hosted or bed-hosted deposit

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This file contains the CGI Earth Resource Shape vocabulary, as defined by the IUGS Commission for Geoscience Information (CGI) Geoscience Terminology Working Group. The vocabulary defines concepts specifying the typical geometrical shape of an Earth Resource (e.g. lenticular, pipelike, irregular etc). By extension, this vocabulary includes all concepts in this conceptScheme, as well as concepts in any previous versions of the scheme.
